    }
   ],
   "execution_count": 25
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8471e589",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Your Answer:**\n",
    "\n",
    "**Shape of histograms for features**\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **Total orders:** The shape of the histogram for total orders is right skewed. Many of the customers have few orders and few customers have many orders.\n",
    "2. **Average days between orders:** This graph is right skewed because most of the values are heavily concentrated at the lower end of the graph. This implies that the average number of users place orders b/w 5-20 days, and few orders are placed frequently.\n",
    "3. **Average shopping hour:** This data for this graph is following normal distribution. This peaks in this graph show that most of the users place orders b/w noon and 4 pm.\n",
    "4. **Average products per order:** This graph is right skewed which implies that most users order few things in each order.\n",
    "5. **Department diversity:** This graph is also right skewed which implies that most users have little diversity in their orders because most orders contain items from 3-6 departments.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Importance of understanding feature distributions**\n",
    "It is important to understand feature distribution because K-means algorithm assumes that the data is supposed to form spherical clusters and calculates using Euclidean distance formula to determine which cluster a point in data would belong to by calculating the distance between the centroid of every cluster and data point that needs classification.\n",
    "\n",
    "If the training dataset is skewed it can lead to biased results which can be prevented by scaling/ transforming the dataset.\n",
    "\n",
    "Understanding feature distribution allows us to ensure that the clusters are based on meaningful patterns in the data.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "acc043da",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "1.2 The Need for Scaling\n",
    "\n",
    "The features in the dataset have very different scales (e.g., `total_orders` vs. `avg_shopping_hour`). Explain why this is a problem for K-means, which relies on Euclidean distance."
   ]
  },
  {
   "metadata": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "source": [
    "**Your Answer:**\n",
    "Different scales are a problem for K-means algorithm because it relies on Euclidean distance for assigning clusters. Euclidean distance is biased towards features with larger scales/ variance because such features contribute more towards distance calculation than features with less variance.\n",
    "\n",
    "For e.g., a scaling of 20 in total_orders affects cluster assignment more than a scale of 2 in avg_shopping_hour even if the latter is more significant for cluster assignment."
   ],
   "id": "9af096e5"
  },
