    "**Your Answer:**\n",
    "\n",
    "**The elbow method:** The elbow method helps to determine the optimal number of clusters by plotting the WCSS (Within-Cluster Sum of Squares) against the selected range of k-values. The point (in the range of k-values) where the improvement slows down is called the \"elbow\" and it the optimal number of clusters.\n",
    "\n",
    "The method involves;\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Selecting a range of k values.\n",
    "2. For each K value, run the K-means algorithm and calculate the wcss, which is the sum of squared distances between each data point and the centroid of its assigned cluster.\n",
    "3.  After calculating the wcss, a plot of wcss array and k-values is generated from which it is evident that as K-value increases the wcss reduces because the distances between centroids and data points reduces.\n",
    "4. The \"Elbow\" is the first point where the value of wcss is the lowest and after which the consecutive values of wcss are uniformly lower than the wcss of the last point or the rate of the decrease in wcss. No drastic reduction in wcss values.\n",
    "5. The K-value of the \"Elbow\" point is considered as the optimal number of clusters.\n",
    "\n",
    "According to the the wcss vs. K-value plot the k value after which the reduction in wcss becomes uniform is 3. The Silhouette score for k = 3 is the highest which further proves that the optimal number of clusters is 3."
   ]
  },
