   "source": [
    "### 3.2 Ethical Considerations\n",
    "\n",
    "Customer clustering is a powerful tool for businesses, but it can have ethical implications. Discuss one potential benefit and one potential harm of using this type of analysis."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0bf05cad",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Your Answer:**\n",
    "\n",
    "**One potential benefit** of Customer Clustering is that it automatically adapts to changes in data and ensures that all the segments of the model reflect the most recent behaviours of customers which makes clustering one of the most effective predictive techniques for companies that want to take a closer look at their customer data.\n",
    "\n",
    "**One potential harm** of Customer Clustering is that just like any other ML model it is sensitive to bias in the training dataset. If the training data is biased or discriminatory, then the model will reinforce the bias and discrimination in its predictions. As a result, it can lead to unfair treatment of customers by denying access to promotions to users in certain clusters or penalize certain users based on their demographic location, income, or background by placing them in less favourable segments."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ef66618e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 3.3 Limitations of K-Means\n",
    "\n",
    "What is one key limitation of the K-means algorithm? For instance, what assumptions does it make about the shape of the clusters?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c277ba17",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**Your Answer:**\n",
    "\n",
    "The key limitation of K-means clustering algorithm is the assumption that the clusters are spherical and/or equally sized. This can be a problem whenever the actual clusters in the data form different shapes like rings, crescents etc., or\n",
    "the density of data is non-uniform.\n",
    "\n",
    "As a result, the algorithm does not give the best global solution because the spherical clusters do not reflect the true structure or distribution of the data."
   ]
  }
